05743nam a22007695i 9781526144997DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192020xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97815261449977 a10.7765/97815261449972doi  a(DE-B1597)659187  a(OCoLC)1132421468  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB 7aHIS0150502bisacsh04a941.07/409222304aThe Cato Street Conspiracy :bPlotting, counter-intelligence and the revolutionary tradition in Britain and Ireland /ced. by Martin Conboy, Jason McElligott. 1aManchester : bManchester University Press, c[2019] 4c©2020  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront matter -- tContents -- tList of figures -- tNotes on contributors -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction ‘We only have to be lucky once’ -- t1 When did they know? The cabinet, informers and Cato Street -- t2 Joining up the dots -- t3 The men they couldn’t hang -- t4 Cato Street in international perspective -- t5 Cato Street and the Caribbean -- t6 Cato Street and the Spencean politics of transnational insurrection -- t7 State witnesses and spies in Irish political trials, 1794–1803 -- t8 The shadow of the Pikeman -- t9 The fate of the transported Cato Street conspirators -- t10 Scripted by whom? -- tAfterword -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn 23 February 1820 a group of radicals were arrested in Cato Street off the Edgware Road in London. They were within sixty minutes of setting out to assassinate the British cabinet. Five of the conspirators were subsequently executed and another five were transported for life to Australia. The plotters were a mixture of English, Scots and Irish tradesmen, and one was a black Jamaican. They were motivated by a desire to avenge the ‘Peterloo’ massacre and intended to declare a republic, which they believed would encourage popular risings in London and across Britain. This volume of essays uses contemporary reports by Home Office spies and informers to assess the seriousness of the conspiracy. It traces the practical and intellectual origins of the plotters’ willingness to use violence; describes the links between Irish and British radicals who were willing to take up arms; makes a contribution to early black history in Britain; examines the European context to events, and follows the lives and careers of those plotters exiled to Australia. A significant contribution to our understanding of a particularly turbulent period of British history, these well-written essays will find an appreciative audience among undergraduates, graduate students and scholars of British and Irish history and literature, black history, and the related fields of intelligence history and Strategic Studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCato Street Conspiracy, 1820. 0aRevolutionarieszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / Georgian Era (1714-1837).2bisacsh  aBlack History.  aInformers.  aInsurrection.  aIreland.  aLondon.  aPeterloo.  aRadicalism.  aRevolution.  aSlavery.1 aChase, Malcolm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConboy, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConboy, Martin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGardner, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaunt, Richard A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanley, Ryan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHannon, Kieran, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcElligott, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 